{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655792"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:05:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:05:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18682"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18682"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.05,0.11,0.84]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11414"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79553"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11414"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18682"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64857"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26438"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26444"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27198"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79553"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe putamen is a major component of the basal ganglia, a group of subcortical nuclei. The basal ganglia are involved in motor control, motor learning, emotions, behaviours and executive functions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the putamen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Controls hormone secretion","Coordinates eye movements","Maintains balance and posture","Processes emotional responses","Regulates motor learning and movement control"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eregulation of motor learning and movement control\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of the putamen. As part of the dorsal striatum, it receives extensive input from the motor and sensory cortex and projects to the globus pallidus. Through these connections, the putamen helps regulate smooth, coordinated movements and motor learning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProcesses emotional responses\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily associated with the limbic system, particularly the amygdala\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EControls hormone secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of the hypothalamus and pituitary gland\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintains balance and posture\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily the function of the cerebellum\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoordinates eye movements\u003C/strong\u003E - This is controlled by the superior colliculus and frontal eye fields\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe putamen works in concert with other basal ganglia structures through direct and indirect pathways to facilitate desired movements while suppressing unwanted ones.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The putamen is part of the dorsal striatum and plays a key role in motor control and learning.","The putamen receives input from the motor and sensory cortex and projects to the globus pallidus.","The putamen is involved in the indirect pathway of movement control which inhibits unwanted movements."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64857"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18682"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64857"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T07:40:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T07:40:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11414"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79553"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"